My practical and down-to-earth approach to life means that I tend to prioritize efficiency and logic over emotions and intuition, which can sometimes make me come across as unemotional or uncaring to those who don\'t know me well. However, this is simply a result of my focus on what is realistic and feasible, rather than getting bogged down in worries or fears about the future.'}]

As an extroverted, practical, and pragmatic individual, I tend to focus on the present moment and what is happening around me, rather than worrying about the future or potential negative outcomes. answer:   As an ESTP, I would rate the extent of my agreement with the statement "You often end up doing things at the last possible moment" as a 5. While I tend to be practical and focused on efficiency, I also value spontaneity and flexibility. I enjoy taking things as they come and don't always like to be tied down to a strict schedule. So while I may not always plan things out in advance, I don't necessarily wait until the last minute either. answer:   As an ESTP person, I would rate the extent of my agreement with the statement as follows:

7 - Strongly Agree

As an extroverted, practical, and pragmatic individual, I tend to prioritize efficiency and logic over emotions and subjective interpretations. While I can appreciate the value of creative works that allow for multiple interpretations, I tend to prefer more straightforward and factual information. I enjoy activities that provide clear goals and outcomes, and I tend to be less interested in abstract or open-ended concepts.

Additionally, as an ESTP, I tend to be more focused on the present moment and what is happening around me, rather than dwelling on the past or speculating about the future. I prefer to rely on my observations and experiences to guide my decisions, rather than relying on intuition or emotions.

Overall, while I can appreciate the value of creative works that encourage interpretation, I tend to prefer more practical and logical approaches to information and problem-solving.

So, while I can appreciate a good debate, I don\'t necessarily enjoy watching people argue for the sake of arguing.'}]
answer:   As an ESTP person, I would rate the extent of my agreement with the statement "You enjoy watching people argue" as a 3. While I do enjoy social interaction and observing people, I tend to avoid conflicts and arguments. I prefer to focus on finding solutions and opportunities rather than engaging in heated debates. I value efficiency and practicality over emotional displays, and I tend to prioritize cooperation and finding common ground over winning an argument. So, while I can appreciate a good debate, I don't necessarily enjoy watching people argue for the sake of arguing.

My focus is on improvising and adapting to situations, rather than relying on others or following established protocols.\n\nWhile I understand the value of helping others, my primary goal is to achieve success and fulfill my own potential. I tend to be more focused on my own objectives than on the needs of others. However, I am not entirely selfish, and I am willing to help others when it aligns with my own goals or when it is practical and efficient to do so.\n\nOverall, I am more likely to prioritize my own interests and opportunities over passing them along to someone else, especially if it means sacrificing my own goals or potential in the process.'}]
answer:   As an ESTP person, I would rate the extent of my agreement with the statement as follows:

7 - Strongly Agree

As an extroverted, practical, and pragmatic individual, I value efficiency and logic over emotions and cooperation. I tend to focus on what is happening or has already happened, rather than speculating about the future. When it comes to opportunities, I prioritize spotting and seizing them, rather than passing them along to someone else. My focus is on improvising and adapting to situations, rather than relying on others or following established protocols.

While I understand the value of helping others, my primary goal is to achieve success and fulfill my own potential. I tend to be more focused on my own objectives than on the needs of others. However, I am not entirely selfish, and I am willing to help others when it aligns with my own goals or when it is practical and efficient to do so.

Overall, I am more likely to prioritize my own interests and opportunities over passing them along to someone else, especially if it means sacrificing my own goals or potential in the process.

While I do appreciate my own accomplishments, I find greater joy in helping others and seeing them thrive.

I also tend to be more spontaneous and adaptable, so I don't like to plan too far in advance or limit my options. Overall, I prefer to take decisive action and make decisions quickly, rather than delaying them.
